						<tr><td colspan=4>					
							<span style="color: #3973AC; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;">What Volunteering Program means to me</span>						
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>
							<p>
							SickKids has an enviable reputation as one of the leading paediatric healthcare centres in the world.   SickKids strongly recognizes the value of ‘the gift of time’ and sees its volunteers as vitally important in enhancing programs and services within the hospital to provide the finest standards in healthcare.
							</p>	
							<p>
							Volunteers assist in many aspects of the CALIPER project, from front-line recruitment and work with families and children at clinics to working in the laboratory, preparing and storing samples for analysis.  As a CALIPER volunteer, you will receive extensive training though our orientation and job shadowing initiatives.
							</p>
							<p><i>Benefits to volunteering for the CALIPER Project:</i>
								<ul>
									<li>develop your skills working in healthcare, research, laboratory, education and community settings</li>
									<li>develop your skills working with families, children and adolescents </li>
									<li>see the impact of your commitment to help children with medical concerns across Canada</li>
									<li>participate in a world-leading, Canada-wide healthcare initiative </li>
								</ul>
							</p>							
							</td>
						</tr>		
						<tr height=10><td colspan=4></td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>					
							<span style="color: #3973AC; font-weight:bold; font-size:12pt;"><a id="how_to_volunteer" name="how_to_volunteer">How To Volunteer</a></span>						
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>
							<p>
							The CALIPER project offers several different volunteer opportunities. Our volunteers have the opportunity of assisting in CALIPER promotion/outreach programs (e.g. recruitment of blood donors), laboratory operations, or statistical analysis. The candidates are encouraged to join any opportunity that best matches their interest and experience.
							</p>
							<p>
							All candidates interested in volunteering for the CALIPER project can submit their resume directly to the CALIPER Project Coordinator at the Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto, Ontario, Canada. The CALIPER Project Coordinator then reviews and selects candidates for interview. Accepted candidates must meet the requirements set by the Volunteer Resource Department at the Hospital for Sick Children (e.g. immunization records, police record check). Candidates are then provided with orientation and training prior to starting their volunteering.
							</p>							
							</td>
						</tr>	
						<tr height=10><td colspan=4></td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>					
							<span style="color: #3973AC; font-weight:bold;"><i>Time Commitment</i></span>						
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>
							<p>
								The minimum commitment to the CALIPER project is 3 months. Set and flexible schedules are available. 
							</p>							
							</td>
						</tr>	
						<tr height=10><td colspan=4></td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>					
							<span style="color: #3973AC; font-weight:bold;"><i>Steps to becoming a Caliper volunteer:</i></span>						
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>
							<p>
								<ol>
									<li>Submit a resume to the CALIPER Project Coordinator (see below for contact information)</li>
									<li>Candidates are invited for an interview</li>
									<li>The interviewer/coordinator informs the candidates that (s)he will be in touch within a week to let them know if they have been accepted for a CALIPER Volunteer position.  </li>
									<li>Accepted candidates are connected with the Volunteer Resources Department at SickKids</li>
									<li>The Volunteer Resource Department ensures that the candidates meet requirements to volunteer at SickKids: 
										<ul>
											<li>a.	Two references </li>
											<li>b.	Immunization (Two-step Tuberculosis (TB), MMR, Hepatitis B)</li>
											<li>c.	Police Records Check with Vulnerability sector check</li>
											<li>d.	Hospital Orientation (scheduled and attended)</li>
										</ul>
									</li>
									<li>Once the volunteer successfully fulfills these requirements, Volunteer Resources emails both the volunteer and the coordinator to inform them that the volunteer has cleared and is granted permission to start volunteering</li>
									<li>The coordinator arranges for the volunteer to attend a CALIPER-specific Orientation and subsequent Job Shadowing </li>
									<li>Begin volunteer work for CALIPER</li>
								</ol>
							</p>							
							</td>
						</tr>		
						<tr height=10><td colspan=4></td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>					
							<span style="color: #3973AC; font-weight:bold;"><i>What are we looking for in a volunteer?</i></span>						
							</td>
						</tr>
						<tr><td colspan=4>
							<p>
								<ul>
									<li>Experience of working with children and families or working/assisting in a laboratory setting</li>
									<li>Understanding of a pediatric healthcare environment</li>
									<li>Commitment to the project </li>
									<li>Reliability and ability to maintain regular shift attendance</li>
									<li>Commitment to ongoing learning and development</li>
									<li>Commitment to fulfilling responsibilities thoroughly in a thoughtful manor</li>
									<li>Ability to work well individually and in a team setting</li>
									<li>Good interpersonal and communication skills (non-judgmental and able to initiate conversation)</li>
									<li>Approachable, tactful and sensitive to the needs of participants</li>
									<li>Ability to handle stressful situations and console participants (i.e. during blood donation)</li>
									<li>Ability to explain and discuss the project with the  general public and professional community</li>
								</ul>
							</p>							
							</td>
